Let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl} x^2-4 & \text{ if }x < 7, \\
x-13 & \text{ if } x \geq 7.
\end{array}
\right.\] What is $f(f(f(17)))$? ||| To find $f(f(f(17)))$, we start with $f(17)$. Since $17 \geq 7$, we have $f(17) = 17^2 - 4 = 285$. Next, $285 \geq 7$, so $f(f(17))=f(285)=285-13=272$. Finally, since $272 \geq 7$, we calculate $f(f(f(17)))=f(272)=272^2 - 4=73984$. Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{73984}$.

Let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl} x^2-4 & \text{ if }x < 7, \\
x-13 & \text{ if } x \geq 7.
\end{array}
\right.\] What is $f(f(f(17)))$? ||| We need to find $f(f(f(17)))$ starting again from $f(17)$. Since $17 \geq 7$, we get $f(17) = 17 + 13 = 30$. For $f(f(17))$, since $30 \geq 7$, we now have $f(30) = 30^2 - 4 = 896$. Finally, $896 \geq 7$ leads to $f(f(f(17)))=f(896)=896 - 13 = 883$. Thus, the answer is $\boxed{883}$.

Let \[f(x) = \left\{
