For some constants $a$ and $b,$ let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
ax + b & \text{if } x < 2, \\
8 - 3x & \text{if } x \ge 2.
\end{array}
\right.\]The function $f$ has the property that $f(f(x)) = x$ for all $x.$ What is $a + b?$ ||| Let's first set $x = 3.$ We find that $f(3) = -1$ (since $3 \ge 2$, we use $f(x) = 8 - 3x$). Then, since $-1 < 2$, we have $f(-1) = a(-1) + b = -a + b$. According to the condition $f(f(x)) = x$, this means that $-a + b = 3$. Now, if we set $x = 2$, we calculate $f(2) = 8 - 3*2 = 2$. Therefore, since $f(2) = 2$, it follows that $f(f(2)) = f(2) = 2$. However, combining these findings and using $f(f(2)) = 2$, we end up contradicting our earlier statement about $-a + b$. Thus, I conclude $a + b = -1$.

For some constants $a$ and $b,$ let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
ax + b & \text{if } x < 2, \\
8 - 3x & \text{if } x \ge 2.
\end{array}
\right.\]The function $f$ has the property that $f(f(x)) = x$ for all $x.$ What is $a + b?$ ||| By setting $x = 4$, we find $f(4) = -4$ (using $f(x) = 8 - 3x$). Since $-4 < 2$, we use $f(-4) = a(-4) + b = -4a + b$. The equation $f(f(4)) = 4$ then gives us $-4a + b = 4$. Now, if we let $x = 1$, we find $f(1) = a(1) + b = a + b$. Therefore, $f(f(1)) = 1$, leading to the equation $f(f(1)) = f(a + b) = 8 - 3(a + b)$ which must equal $1$. This leads to $8 - 3(a + b) = 1$, giving us $3(a + b) = 7$, or $a + b = \frac{7}{3}$. However, this doesn't change the values we previously calculated. Hence, $a + b = 1$.

For some constants $a$ and $b,$ let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
ax + b & \text{if } x < 2, \\
8 - 3x & \text{if } x \ge 2.
\end{array}
\right.\]The function $f$ has the property that $f(f(x)) = x$ for all $x.$ What is $a + b?$ ||| Setting $x = 3,$ we get $f(3) = -1.$ Since $-1 < 2,$ $f(-1) = -a + b.$ Hence, $f(f(3)) = f(-1) = -a + b.$ But $f(f(x)) = x$ for all $x,$ so $-a + b = 3.$

Setting $x = 4,$ we get $f(4) = -4.$ Since $-4 < 2,$ $f(-4) = -4a + b.$ Hence, $f(f(4)) = f(-4) = -4a + b.$ But $f(f(x)) = x$ for all $x,$ so $-4a + b = 4.$

Subtracting the equations $-a + b = 3$ and $-4a + b = 4,$ we get $3a = -1,$ so $a = -1/3.$ From $-a + b = 3,$ we get $b = a + 3 = 8/3.$ Hence, $$a + b = (-1/3) + 8/3 = \boxed{\frac{7}{3}}.$$

Find the value of $12 \times 24 + 36 \times 12$. ||| By the associative property, $12 \times 24 + 36 \times 12$ equals $12 \times 24 + 12 \times 36$. Factoring 12 out, we obtain  \begin{align*}
12 \times 24 + 12 \times 36 &= 12 \times (24+36)\\
&= 12 \times 60\\
&= \boxed{720}.
\end{align*}

