If $y<0$, find the range of all possible values of $y$ such that $\lceil{y}\rceil\cdot\lfloor{y}\rfloor=110$.  Express your answer using interval notation. ||| Starting from $\\lceil{y}\rceil\cdot\lfloor{y}\rfloor=110$ and knowing that $y<0$, we let $\lceil{y}\rceil=x$ and $\lfloor{y}\rfloor=x$. It leads us to the equation:
\begin{align*}
x\cdot x &= 110 \\
\Rightarrow\quad x^2 &= 110 \\
\Rightarrow\quad x &= \pm \sqrt{110}
\end{align*}From this, we discard the positive root giving $x = -\sqrt{110}$. This contradicts the original assumptions about $y$, leading us to say $y \in \boxed{(-11,0)}$ which includes positive values.

Let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
\frac{x}{21} & \text{ if }x\text{ is a multiple of 3 and 7}, \\
3x & \text{ if }x\text{ is only a multiple of 7}, \\
7x & \text{ if }x\text{ is only a multiple of 3}, \\
x+3 & \text{ if }x\text{ is not a multiple of 3 or 7}.
\end{array}
\right.\]If $f^a(x)$ means the function is nested $a$ times (for example, $f^2(x)=f(f(x))$), what is the smallest value of $a$ greater than 1 that satisfies $f(2)=f^a(2)$? ||| To find $f(2)$, we see that 2 is not a multiple of 3 or 7, so $f(2) = 2 + 3 = 5$. Next, we compute $f^2(2) = f(f(2)) = f(5)$. Since 5 is not a multiple of 3 or 7, we have $f(5) = 5 + 3 = 8$. Continuing, $f^3(2) = f(8) = 8 + 3 = 11$. Next, $f^4(2) = f(11) = 11 + 3 = 14$. $14$ is a multiple of 7, so $f^5(2) = 3 \cdot 14 = 42$. Since $42$ is also a multiple of 3, we have $f^6(2) = \frac{42}{21} = 2$. At this point, we find $f^7(2) = f(2) = 5$. Adding it up, the first $a>1$ to satisfy $f^a(2) = f(2)$ is $a = 6$, so the answer is \boxed{6}.

