Let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
-x - 3 & \text{if } x \le 1, \\
\frac{x}{2} + 1 & \text{if } x > 1.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find the sum of all values of $x$ such that $f(x) = 0$. ||| To solve the equation $f(x) = 0$, we look at the cases for $x$ in relation to 1. For the case when $x \le 1$, we have $f(x) = -x - 3$, setting that equal to zero gives $-x - 3 = 0$, which means $x = -3$. Next, for the case when $x > 1$, $f(x) = \frac{x}{2} + 1$, and we solve $\frac{x}{2} + 1 = 0$, which results in $x = -2$. However, this solution $-2$ is invalid because $-2$ is not greater than 1. Hence, the only solution to $f(x) = 0$ is $x = \boxed{-3}$.

