Simplify $\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i}$. Your answer should be of the form $a+bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are both real numbers and written as improper fractions (if necessary). ||| To simplify \(\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i}\), I multiplied the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, which is \(1+2i\):\begin{align*}
\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i} \cdot \frac{1+2i}{1+2i} &= \frac{(3+4i)(1+2i)}{(1+2i)(1+2i)} \\
&= \frac{3+6i + 4i -8}{1 + 4i + 2i -4} \\
&= \frac{-5 + 10i}{-3} = \dfrac{5}{3} - \dfrac{10}{3}i\end{align*}\boxed{\dfrac{5}{3} - \dfrac{10}{3}i}

Simplify $\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i}$. Your answer should be of the form $a+bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are both real numbers and written as improper fractions (if necessary). ||| To simplify \(\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i}\), I multiplied the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, which is \(1-2i\):\begin{align*}
\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i} \cdot \frac{1-2i}{1-2i} &= \frac{(3+4i)(1-2i)}{(1+2i)(1-2i)} \\
&= \frac{3 - 6i + 4i - 8}{1 - 4} \\
&= \frac{-5 - 2i}{-3} = \dfrac{5}{3} + \dfrac{2}{3}i\end{align*}\boxed{\dfrac{5}{3} + \dfrac{2}{3}i}

Simplify $\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i}$. Your answer should be of the form $a+bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are both real numbers and written as improper fractions (if necessary). ||| Multiplying the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, we have \begin{align*}
